<font color="#FF0000">FRAYED THREAD</font><br>
<tt>Wed Oct  8  0:43:53 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I have been away from this site fighting my own demons. Stopped back for a peek.   At the risk of getting flamed myself, I believe something needs to be said about this thread.<br>
The posts on this site are rather disturbing to me.  Not because of the language (which has sunk to an all time low) but the lack of tolerance which I thought Vietnam vets were trying to work toward and generally bend over backwards amongst ourselves to live. Art, what you have written in the past shows depth, this tangent is beneath you.<br><br>
We all knew Spatz always took delight in &quot;stirring the pot&quot; and as a result took him with a grain of salt.  If he has truly left, expect to be bored.  Spatz was the guy everyone loved to hate. The sole voice in the wilderness of former protestors with enough balls to take on Vietnam vets no less.  He'd open his mouth and firmly stick his foot in it on our turf. But he was willing to listen, wanted to understand, would consider, and would even capitulate when we jumped on him and explained the other side of the issue.  Just because he was a protestor doesn't mean he was a coward. Just like every soldier wasn't a women and baby killer.  There has been too much name calling.  It isn't productive and it is probably a symptom of the Ptsd. <br><br>
You question how anyone (anonymous) could stick up for Spatz unless they are Spatz himself.  Pulling myself up to my full feminine five feet tall I can attest to the fact  I am not now, nor have I ever been, or would I ever want to be Barry Spatz. But, here I find myself defending his right to participate on this site.    An insight I received from Spatz over his tenure here is that protestors with moral convictions as the basis of their protests may feel ignored and unappreciated just like vets.   Protestors/those who served -  opposite sides of the same coin. Both sides taking risks, wondering years later why they never got the respect or rewards they believed they deserved for their stand. (Picked some of this up on other net sites - not just a Barry Spatz phenomena.) Personally I believe that part of the healing process requires protestors and vets alike to forgive each other and stop defending 30 year old choices.  I would love to see not only vets but former protestors able to meet at The Wall to honor and grieve the loss of our fallen brothers and sisters.  Am I  an optimist or what?  (That is a rhetorical question!  Don't feel obligated to tell me how naive I am.  After all that's how I ended up in Vietnam in the first place... cause you guys were there and shouldn't have to go it alone.) <br>

<p><code>--   (Class Lass) </code><p>


